'''Jason Michael Kipnis''' (born April 3, 1987; nicknamed "'''Kip'''")<ref name="CSTV bio">{{cite web|url=http://thesundevils.cstv.com/sports/m-basebl/mtt/kipnis_jason00.html |title=Player Bio: Jason Kipnis |publisher=Thesundevils.cstv.com |date= |accessdate=August 3, 2011}}</ref> is an American [[baseball]] player who plays [[second base]] for the [[Cleveland Indians]]. He attended [[Glenbrook North High School]], where he earned three [[varsity letter|letter]]s playing baseball for the Glenbrook North Spartans. He attended the [[University of Kentucky]], but transferred to [[Arizona State University]] after two years. In college, Kipnis was an [[All American]] and the 2009 [[Pacific-10]] Conference Player of the Year for the [[Arizona State Sun Devils|Sun Devils]].

The Indians selected Kipnis in the second round of the [[2009 Major League Baseball Draft]]. In 2010, he was named the Indians' Minor League Player of the Year, and a ''[[Baseball America]]'' Minor League All Star. Prior to the 2011 season, ''[[Baseball Prospectus]]'' ranked him as the top Indians prospect and the 28th-highest prospect in baseball. At mid-season, ''Baseball America'' rated him as baseball's 31st-best prospect.<ref name="CSTV bio"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.baseballamerica.com/today/prospects/rankings/top-100-prospects/2011/2611326.html |title=Baseball America 2011 Top 100 Prospects |work=Baseball America |date=February 23, 2011 |author= |accessdate=July 22, 2011}}(rating Kipnis #54 in its list of top 100 prospects)</ref> He was called up from the minor leagues on July 22, [[2011 Cleveland Indians season|2011]]. In 2012, he became the starting second baseman of the Indians.

==Early life==
Jason Michael Kipnis was born on April 3, 1987 in [[Northbrook, Illinois]], a suburb of Chicago.<ref name="thebaseballcube1">{{cite web|url=http://www.thebaseballcube.com/Awards/K/Jason-Kipnis.shtml |title=Jason Kipnis Awards |publisher=The Baseball Cube |date= |accessdate=July 22, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://heebmagazine.com/the-hebrew-nation-needs-its-own-world-series/4747 |title=The Hebrew Nation Needs Its Own World Series |work=Heeb Magazine |date=October 28, 2009 |first=Joshua|last= Neuman |accessdate=July 22, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://njjewishnews.com/kaplanskorner/2011/06/14/kipnis-coming/ |title=Kipnis coming? |work=New Jersey Jewish News |date=June 14, 2011 |first=Ron |last=Kaplan|accessdate=July 22, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Fine |first=Jeremy |url=http://www.jewishjournal.com/the_great_rabbino/item/where_should_we_look_now_20100926/ |title=Where Should We Look Now? |work=Jewish Journal |date=September 26, 2010 |accessdate=July 22, 2011}}</ref> He was the fourth child born to Kay and Mark Kipnis. He has two older brothers, Blair and Todd. His older sister Amanda played [[softball]] at the [[University of Maryland]].<ref name="CSTV bio"/><ref name="Deep">{{cite news|last=Murr |first=Chuck |url=http://northbrook.patch.com/articles/pro-baseball-career-has-deep-roots-in-northbrook |title=Pro Baseball Career Has Deep Roots in Northbrook |work=Northbrook Patch|date=March 29, 2011 |author= |accessdate=July 22, 2011}}</ref><ref name="ukathletics1">{{cite web|url=http://www.ukathletics.com/genrel/070605aao.html |title=Player Bio: Jason Kipnis |publisher=Ukathletics.com |date= |accessdate=July 23, 2011}}</ref> As a child, his father played an important role in his baseball life. He played Little League and [[American Legion Baseball]]. Though Kipnis played baseball, football and soccer while growing up, he said there was never any question that his goal was to become a professional baseball player.<ref name=Deep />

==High school==
Kipnis attended [[Glenbrook North High School]] in Northbrook, graduating in 2005.<ref name=pro>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=XU14b2Ft4ccC&pg=PA133&dq=jason+kipnis+baseball&hl=en&ei=KhEpTsitO4fJgQedj7mgCw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCkQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Baseball Prospectus 2011 |publisher=John Wiley and Sons |date= 2011 |first=Steven |last=Goldman|ISBN=0-470-62206-7 |accessdate=July 23, 2011}}</ref><ref name="Chases">{{cite news|last=Martinez |first=Robert |url=http://northbrook.patch.com/articles/glenbrook-north-grad-chases-major-league-baseball-dreams |title=Glenbrook North Grad Chases Major League Baseball Dreams |author= |work=Northbrook Patch |date=November 29, 2010 |accessdate=July 23, 2011}}</ref> He earned three [[varsity letter|letter]]s in baseball for the Glenbrook North Spartans and was selected as team captain twice. He played shortstop, center field and pitcher.<ref name="CSTV bio"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/g/GooglePM/SKRB/lib00908,110D638C0969BE88.html |title=Napoleon knows how to deliver |work= Skokie Review |date=July 8, 2004 |author=Dennis Mahoney |accessdate=July 22, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=PGHB&p_multi=GANB&p_theme=pghb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=110D634172C2EF20&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=Northbrook hits rough stretch|work=Glenview Announcements|date=July 1, 2004 |first=Jim |last=Coffman |accessdate=July 22, 2011}}</ref> As an all-conference junior, Kipnis batted .455 with a school-record 11 [[home run]]s. As a senior, Kipnis batted .521 with a .690 [[on base percentage]] and 32 [[stolen base]]s in 32 attempts; he was named first-team all-state and the [[Central Suburban League]] [[Most Valuable Player]].<ref name="CSTV bio"/><ref name="ukathletics1"/> He was named all-conference in both his junior and senior seasons.<ref name="CSTV bio"/><ref name="Media Guide">{{cite book|url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/asu/sports/m-basebl/auto_pdf/08-basebl-mg-sec01.pdf |title=Arizona State Sun Devil Baseball Media Guide| first=Randy |last=Policar |format=PDF |date=2008 | publisher= Ben Franklin Press, Inc. |accessdate=July 24, 2011}}</ref>

As a freshman at Glenbrook North, Kipnis played soccer, setting the school's single-season goal scoring record with 41.<ref name="ukathletics1"/> He also played [[American football|football]] there in 2003 and 2004.<ref name="Deep"/> An All-Conference [[wide receiver]],<ref name="CSTV bio"/><ref name="ukathletics1"/><ref name="Highlights">{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/team/player.jsp?player_id=543401 |title=Jason Kipnis Stats, Bio, Photos, Highlights |publisher=mlb.com |date= |accessdate=July 24, 2011}}</ref> Kipnis set single-season school records for receptions, yards, and touchdowns.<ref name="CSTV bio"/> He also established school records for career receptions and receiving yards.<ref name="Media Guide"/><ref name="cleveland1">{{cite news|author=Chuck Crow |url=http://www.cleveland.com/tribe/index.ssf/2011/02/cleveland_indians_prospect_wat_5.html |title=Cleveland Indians prospect watch: Jason Kipnis |work=The Plain Dealer |date=February 23, 2011 |accessdate=July 24, 2011}}</ref> As a senior in 2004, Kipnis had 49 pass receptions for 956 yards and 10 [[touchdown]]s.<ref name=PP/> His 2004 totals remain Glenbrook North single-season records for receptions, receiving yards, and receiving touchdowns.<ref name=GNR>{{cite web|title=Glenbrook North Spartans Football: Individual Records|publisher=|url=}}</ref> Kipnis still holds the school's career record with 1,247 receiving yards.<ref name=GNR/> In December 2004, the ''[[Pioneer Press]]'' sports staff selected Kipnis as a member of its "2004 North Stars," the all-star football team for the [[Central Suburban League]]'s North Division. In announcing its selection, the ''Pioneer Press'' noted: "Quite simply one of the top receivers in the state, a player who piled up impressive numbers despite the fact the Spartans averaged barely 15 passing attempts per game."<ref name="Highlights"/><ref name="cleveland1"/><ref name=PP>{{cite news|title=Kelly stands out in final grid year |author=Dennis Mahoney|newspaper=Skokie Review|date=December 9, 2004|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_action=doc&p_docid=110D638E5D6957B8&p_docnum=1&s_dlid=DL0111072414265824331&s_ecproduct=DOC&s_ecprodtype=&s_trackval=GooglePM&s_siteloc=&s_referrer=&s_username=cbl62&s_accountid=AC0111072414094924843&s_upgradeable=no}}</ref>

==College==
[[File:Jason Kipnis ASU.jpg|240px|thumb|right|Kipnis with the [[Arizona State Sun Devils]], in 2009]]
After graduating from high school in 2005, Kipnis attended the [[University of Kentucky]] and then [[Arizona State University]]. At the University of Kentucky, Kipnis [[Redshirt (college sports)|red-shirted]] during the 2006 baseball season. In the spring of 2007, Kipnis began competing with the [[Kentucky Wildcats]] during baseball games, where he batted .337 with a .450 on base percentage as an outfielder while stealing 11 bases in 12 attempts in 34 games.<ref name="CSTV bio"/><ref name="Chases"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cstv.com/sports/m-basebl/stories/090607aad.html |title=Same Faces, New Places; Some teams strike gold in transfers|publisher=CSTV |date=September 6, 2007 |author=Douglas Kroll |accessdate=July 22, 2011}}</ref> In February of that year, Kipnis was awarded [[Southeastern Conference]] Freshman of the Week honors.<ref name="Media Guide"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wkyt.com/sports/headlines/6332247.html |title=Cats' Coughlin Receives National Honor |publisher=Wkyt.com |date=March 6, 2007 |author= |accessdate=July 22, 2011}}</ref> In the summer before his sophomore year, Kipnis played for the [[Covington Lumberjacks]] of the [[Valley Baseball League]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/g/GooglePM/VNRB/lib01574,11AC3DD7DA0934F8.html |title=Jacks Jolt Turks |work=Daily News-Record |date=August 1, 2007 |first=Mike |last=Barber |accessdate=July 22, 2011}}</ref> a [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]]-sanctioned [[List of collegiate summer baseball leagues|collegiate summer baseball league]] in the [[Shenandoah Valley]] region of [[Virginia]]. He batted .318 with a .505 on base percentage and 24 stolen bases.<ref name="blogspot1">{{cite web|author=Paul DePodesta |url=http://itmightbedangerous.blogspot.com/2008/06/jason-kipnis-2.html |title=You Go First: Jason Kipnis #2 |publisher=Itmightbedangerous.blogspot.com |date=June 5, 2008 |author= [[Paul DePodesta]]|accessdate=July 22, 2011}}</ref>

After two years at the University of Kentucky, Kipnis transferred to Arizona State University. He played baseball for the [[Arizona State Sun Devils|Sun Devils]] and double-majored in psychology and sociology.<ref name="Chases"/><ref name=Dirtbag>{{cite web|last=Valade|first=Jodie|title=Cleveland Indians' Jason Kipnis: Proud to be a 'Dirtbag'|url=http://www.cleveland.com/tribe/index.ssf/2012/06/cleveland_indians_jason_kipnis_proud_to_be_a_dirtbag.html|publisher=[[The Plain Dealer]]|accessdate=October 23, 2012|date=June 2, 2012}}</ref> In an interview, Kipnis stated that the University of Kentucky wasn't the right fit for him and that ASU's college baseball reputation would make it a better fit.<ref name="JK interview" />

In 2008, Kipnis batted .371 with 14 home runs and 73 [[runs batted in]]. He finished second in the league with 24 stolen bases in 28 attempts.<ref name="azcentral1">{{cite news|last=Metcalfe |first=Jeff |url=http://www.azcentral.com/sports/asu/articles/2009/04/16/20090416asubase0417.html |title=ASU baseball: Kipnis making the most of return |publisher=Azcentral.com |date=April 16, 2009 |accessdate=July 23, 2011}}</ref> Kipnis primarily played center field, but played all outfield positions and second base; he batted leadoff part of the time.<ref name="blogspot1"/><ref name="Same Faces">{{cite news|url=http://www.cstv.com/sports/m-basebl/stories/052908abx.html |title=Same Faces, New Places; Some teams strike gold in transfers |publisher=CSTV |date=May 29, 2008 |author=Douglas Kroll |accessdate=July 23, 2011}}</ref><ref name="reduces">{{cite news|last=Metcalfe |first=Jeff |url=http://www.azcentral.com/sports/asu/articles/2008/04/24/20080424asubase.html |title=ASU's Kipnis reduces, produces |publisher=Azcentral.com |date=April 24, 2008 |accessdate=July 23, 2011}}</ref> In 2008, Kipnis became the second Arizona State player to win the [[American Baseball Coaches Association]] (ABCA) [[Pacific-10 Conference]] Newcomer of the Year. (Teammate [[Ike Davis]] earned the award two years earlier.) Kipnis was named second-team All America by the ABCA and named third-team All-American outfielder by ''[[Baseball America]]''.<ref name="CSTV bio"/><ref name="thebaseballcube1"/><ref name="Same Faces"/> In May 2008, he won the Pacific 10 Player of the Week award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cstv.com/sports/m-basebl/stories/052708aat.html |title=Jason Kipnis Named Pac-10 Player of the Week |publisher=CSTV |date=May 27, 2008 |author= |accessdate=July 22, 2011}}</ref> In June, the [[San Diego Padres]] drafted Kipnis during the fourth round of the [[2008 Major League Baseball Draft]]. However, Kipnis opted to remain in college at Arizona State,<ref name="Baseball Cube Statistics">{{cite web|url=http://www.thebaseballcube.com/profile.asp?P=/Jason-Kipnis.shtml |title=Jason Kipnis Statistics |publisher=The Baseball Cube |date= |accessdate=July 23, 2011}}</ref> becoming the seventh-highest player in the draft who chose not to sign.<ref>{{cite news|last=Goldstein |first=Kevin |url=http://www.baseballprospectus.com/article.php?articleid=8681 |title=Future Shock: Tuesday's Monday Ten Pack |work=Baseball Prospectus |date=March 31, 2009 |accessdate=July 22, 2011}}</ref> He decided not to sign with the Padres because he felt he hadn't fully matured and accomplished everything in college.<ref name="JK interview">{{cite web|title=Jason Kipnis interview|url=http://www.muscleprodigy.com/sport-prodigy-of-month.php?sportProdigyID=5|publisher=Muscle Prodigy|accessdate=October 24, 2012}}</ref> Regarding Kipnis' success, Arizona State coach [[Pat Murphy (baseball coach)|Pat Murphy]] observed: "I love that kid. He's tough as nails, and really hard on himself."<ref name="reduces"/> Moreover, [[Paul DePodesta]], San Diego Padres front office assistant and former [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] general manager, described him as "a pesky player who is a very tough out, hitting the ball to all fields and running the bases aggressively ... [who] plays very hard and is surprisingly strong."<ref name="blogspot1"/> In the summer of 2008, Kipnis played for the [[Cotuit Kettleers]] in the [[Cape Cod League]],<ref>{{cite news|author= |url=http://www.capecodonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20080628/SPORTS/806280342 |title=Cape League: Brewster takes East lead |work=Cape Cod Times |date= June 28, 2008|accessdate=July 22, 2011}}</ref>  a [[List of collegiate summer baseball leagues|collegiate summer baseball league]] located on [[Cape Cod]] in [[Massachusetts]].

In 2009, Kipnis was the team's leadoff hitter and batted .384 with a .500 on base percentage and a .709 slugging percentage. He finished with 16 home runs, 71 RBIs, 27 steals in 33 attempts, 51 walks and 32 strikeouts.  The [[National Collegiate Baseball Writers Association]] (NCBWA), ''Baseball America'', and ''[[Collegiate Baseball]]'' named Kipnis the Pac-10 Conference Player of the Year, a Pac-10 Conference All-Star outfielder, and a First Team College All-American outfielder.<ref name="thebaseballcube1"/><ref name="Chases"/><ref>{{cite news|author=Marc Means |url=http://www.minorleaguebaseball.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090803&content_id=6219938&vkey=pr_t545&fext=.jsp&sid=t545 |title=Scrappers Add 2nd Round Draft Pick to Roster |publisher=Minorleaguebaseball.com |date= August 3, 2009|accessdate=July 22, 2011}}</ref> [[Rivals.com]] rated Kipnis the number one outfielder in the nation.<ref name="azcentral1"/>

Over two seasons, Kipnis batted .378 with 30 home runs, 144 RBIs, 142 runs, 37 doubles, 10 triples, and 51 stolen bases in 474 at bats for the Sun Devils.<ref name="Deep"/><ref name="Chases"/> His efforts lead him to be considered the best hitter on the [[Arizona State Sun Devils|Sun Devils]].<ref name=pro/><ref name="Chases"/><ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=CSJqZTpumLYC&pg=PA235&dq=jason+kipnis&hl=en&ei=0A8pTvbDOZSTtweK0O36Cw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CC0Q6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=jason%20kipnis&f=false |title=Life Is Yours to Win: Lessons Forged from the Purpose, Passion, and Magic of Baseball|ISBN=1-4391-8693-6 |publisher=Simon and Schuster |date= 2011|author=Augie Garrido, Kevin Costner |accessdate=July 22, 2011}}</ref>

==Minor leagues==
===2009===
The [[Cleveland Indians]] drafted Kipnis in the second round (63rd overall) of the [[2009 Major League Baseball Draft]], and he received a [[signing bonus]] of $575,000.<ref name="thebaseballcube1"/><ref name="google2">{{cite book|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=OsgRQcR8YHcC&pg=PA165&dq=jason+kipnis&hl=en&ei=0A8pTvbDOZSTtweK0O36Cw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&ved=0CDMQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=jason%20kipnis&f=false |title=Baseball Prospectus 2010 |publisher=John Wiley and Sons |date= 2010 |author= [[Will Carroll]], [[Steven Goldman]], [[Christina Kahrl]]|ISBN=0-470-55840-7|accessdate=July 22, 2011}}</ref> In 2009, the first-year minor leaguer batted .306 for the [[Mahoning Valley Scrappers]] of the [[Class A-Short Season|Short-Season A]] classification [[New York-Penn League]], playing left and center field.<ref name="Deep"/><ref name=pro/><ref name="Baseball Cube Statistics"/> While Kipnis appeared to be a good prospect as an outfielder, the Indians hoped that Kipnis would be even more valuable as a second baseman.<ref name="google2"/> He felt he could have more success in the majors if he played second base, particularly because of Cleveland's difficulties at that position in recent years.<ref name=Loafing>{{cite web|last=Pluto|first=Terry|title='Loafing' is a dirty word to a baseball dirtbag|url=http://www.cleveland.com/pluto/blog/index.ssf/2012/07/loafing_is_a_dirty_word_to_a_b.html|publisher=[[The Plain Dealer]]|accessdate=October 24, 2012|date=July 3, 2012}}</ref> ''Baseball America'' ranked him the fifth-best player in the league.<ref>{{cite news|author=Chuck Crow |url=http://www.cleveland.com/ohio-sports-blog/index.ssf/2009/10/cleveland_indians.html |title=Cleveland Indians prospects do moderately well in ''Baseball America'' minor league rankings |work=The Plain Dealer |date=October 15, 2009 |author= |accessdate=July 23, 2011}}</ref> During this time, ''[[Baseball Prospectus]]'' rated him the Indians' eighth-best prospect, describing Kipnis as "fitting great baseball intelligence, a lot of intensity, and surprising tools into a small package. He works the count extremely well and makes consistently hard contact, and he has some surprising pop for his size."<ref>{{cite news|last=Goldstein |first=Kevin |url=http://www.baseballprospectus.com/article.php?articleid=9784 |title=Future Shock: Indians Top 11 Prospects |work=Baseball Prospectus |date=November 20, 2009 |author= |accessdate=July 23, 2011}}</ref>

===2010===
In 2010, Kipnis batted .300 for the [[Kinston Indians]] of the [[Carolina League]].<ref name="Deep"/> Kipnis was promoted from Kinston to the [[Akron Aeros]] of the AA [[Eastern League (baseball)|Eastern League]] on June 10, 2010.<ref name="Keeper for Aeros">{{cite web|last=Feerasta|first=Aniqua|title=Kipnis showing to be keeper for Aeros|url=http://www.akron.com/akron-ohio-sports-news.asp?aID=9569|publisher=West Side Leader|accessdate=October 24, 2012|date=July 15, 2010}}</ref> He hit .311 for the Aeros and won the Aeros Player of the Week Award twice.<ref name="Deep"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.oursportscentral.com/services/releases/?id=4032641 |title=Kipnis Wins Aeros Player of the Week Award |publisher=OurSports Central |author= |date=June 21, 2010 |accessdate=July 23, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.oursportscentral.com/services/releases/?id=4057732 |title=Aeros Name Alex White Player of the Week |publisher=OurSports Central |date=July 26, 2010 |author= |accessdate=July 23, 2011}}</ref> ''Baseball America'' ranked Kipnis the ninth-best prospect in the Eastern League.<ref name="Pitcher Of Year">{{cite news|url=http://www.witn.com/sports/headlines/White_Named_Indians_Minor_League_Player_Of_Year_105559668.html?ref=668 |title=White Named Indians Minor League Pitcher Of Year |publisher=Witn.com |date=October 22, 2010 |author= |accessdate=July 23, 2011}}</ref> At the same time, Kipnis made a successful conversion to second base.<ref name="Deep"/><ref name=K-Tribe>{{cite web|last=Hall|first=David|title=K-Tribe's Kipnis embraces new job|url=http://www.jdnews.com/sports/kipnis-77660-indians-second.html|publisher=Jd News|accessdate=October 23, 2012|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20100427145641/http://www.jdnews.com/sports/kipnis-77660-indians-second.html|archivedate=April 27, 2010|date=April 25, 2010}}</ref>

He joined the [[Triple-A (baseball)|AAA]] [[Columbus Clippers]] for their playoffs. Kipnis batted .455 in five games, and [[hit for the cycle]] on September 17 in the Clippers<U+2019> victory that clinched the [[International League]] title.<ref name="Deep"/><ref name="Pitcher Of Year"/> His big game was voted second in the 2010 Fans Choice "Best Game" [[Minor League Baseball Yearly Awards]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Hill |first=Benjamin |url=http://www.minorleaguebaseball.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20101101&content_id=15940844&vkey=news_milb&fext=.jsp |title=Fans name top Minors team, game |publisher=Minorleaguebaseball.com |date=November 1, 2010 |author= |accessdate=July 23, 2011}}</ref> Veteran catcher [[Luke Carlin]] said: <blockquote>They bring up Kipnis from Akron, and we look at this little guy and say, 'Where did he come from, and what is he doing here?' We were teasing him, and all he does is go out and hit about a million. I mean, here's this little infielder and they put him in the fifth spot ... What's that about? He goes out and hits for the cycle.<ref name="Deep"/></blockquote>

For 2010, Kipnis led the Indians minor league system in hits (159) and runs (96). He finished tied for third in triples (8), fourth in doubles (32), and tied for fifth in both home runs (16) and RBIs (74). He batted a combined .313.<ref name="Pitcher Of Year"/><ref>{{cite news|author=Jim Ingraham |url=http://news-herald.com/articles/2011/01/30/sports/nh3567430.txt?viewmode=fullstory |title=Indians prospect Jason Kipnis is on the fast track to the big leagues |work=The News-Herald|date=January 30, 2011 |first= Jim |last=Ingraham|accessdate=July 23, 2011}}</ref> He was named the Indians' 2010 Minor League Player of the Year (the "[[Lou Boudreau]] Award"), and was named a 2010 ''Baseball America'' Minor League All-Star.<ref name="2B Jason">{{cite news|url=http://cleveland.indians.mlb.com/news/press_releases/press_release.jsp?ymd=20110705&content_id=21434308&vkey=pr_cle&fext=.jsp&c_id=cle |title=2B Jason Kipnis named Indians Minor League Player of The Week |publisher=mlb.com |date=July 5, 2011|author= |accessdate=July 22, 2011}}</ref><ref name="Minor League All Star">{{cite web|title=Final edition reveals our Minor League All-Star Team|url=http://www.baseballamerica.com/today/prospects/prospect-hot-sheet/2010/2610648.html|publisher=Baseball America|accessdate=October 23, 2012|date=September 10, 2010}}</ref>

After the 2010 season, Kipnis played for the [[Peoria Javelinas]] in the [[Arizona Fall League]]. He batted .296 and tied for fifth in the league in RBIs (19). He was named to the Arizona Fall League Rising Stars Game, and he wrote a blog for [[MLB.com]] during his time in the league.<ref name="Chases"/><ref name="Highlights"/><ref name="cleveland1"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cleveland.com/tribe/index.ssf/2010/11/bud_selig_says_major_league_ba.html |title=Bud Selig says Major League Baseball players, owners are playing nice|work=The Plain Dealer |date= November 18, 2010|first=Paul |last=Hoynes |accessdate=July 23, 2011}}</ref> ''Baseball Prospectus'' ranked him as Cleveland's top prospect.<ref>{{cite news|last=Goldstein |first=Kevin |url=http://www.baseballprospectus.com/article.php?articleid=12505 |title=Future Shock: Cleveland Indians Top 11 Prospects |work=Baseball Prospectus |date=November 30, 2010 |accessdate=July 23, 2011}}</ref>

===2011===
''Baseball Prospectus 2011'' reported that Kipnis was "a compact athlete who works the count, and consistently barrels up balls with enough power for 15<U+2013>20 home runs annually in the big leagues."<ref name=pro/> Indians Manager [[Manny Acta]] described him as: "a [[blue collar]], dirt bag, run-through-a-wall, relentless type of guy."<ref>{{cite news|author=Chuck Crow |url=http://www.cleveland.com/tribe/index.ssf/2011/03/manny_acta_likes_jason_kipnis.html |title=Grady Sizemore will start covering the bases in his comeback return: Indians Insider |work=The Plain Dealer |date= |accessdate=July 24, 2011}}</ref> Writer [[John Sickels]] said Kipnis is "quite strong and has plenty of bat speed. His feel for the strike zone is impressive, and he has no problem generating power. He seems to handle both fastballs and breaking stuff well, makes adjustments, and can handle left-handed pitching just fine."<ref>{{cite news|last=Boring |first=Kent |url=http://www.minorleagueball.com/2011/7/8/2265182/prospect-of-the-day-jason-kipnis-2b-cleveland-indians |title=Prospect of the Day: Jason Kipnis, 2B, Cleveland Indians |publisher=Minor League Ball |date=July 8, 2011 |accessdate=July 24, 2011}}</ref>

''Baseball Prospectus'' ranked him as the 28th-highest prospect in baseball (".300 hitter, with 12<U+2013>18 home runs") and the best in the organization.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wtam.com/cc-common/news/sections/sportsarticle.html?feed=208459&article=8865570 |title=Kipnis called up from Triple-A; Converted second baseman can play outfield, Valbuena sent down |publisher=WTAM |date= |author= |accessdate=July 24, 2011}}</ref> [[Jim Bowden]] ranked him the 39th-best prospect in baseball ("He made great progress defensively this past year, and there is no doubt he should be a .300, 15 HR, 70 RBI type offensive 2B in the future").<ref name=pro/><ref>{{cite news|author=Thomas Ondrey |url=http://www.cleveland.com/ohio-sports-blog/index.ssf/2011/02/pm_cleveland_indians_links_48.html |title=P.M. Cleveland Indians links: Shin-Soo Choo the reliable standout on a roster full with questions |work=The Plain Dealer |date=February 12, 2011 |accessdate=July 24, 2011}}</ref> ''[[Baseball America]]'' initially ranked him as the 54th-best prospect in baseball (and the second-best second base prospect, as well as the second-best prospect in the Indians organization),<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.baseballamerica.com/today/prospects/rankings/top-100-prospects/2011/2611326.html |title=2011 Top 100 Prospects: 41<U+2013>60 |work=Baseball America |date=February 23, 2011 |accessdate=July 22, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://nbcsports.msnbc.com/id/41391530/sports/player_news |title=Chisenhall, Kipnis to start season in minors |publisher=NBC Sports |date=February 2, 2011 |accessdate=July 24, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Evans |first=Brad |url=http://sports.yahoo.com/fantasy/blog/roto_arcade/post/Rundown-Jason-Kipnis-small-in-stature-enormous?urn=fantasy-wp4932 |title=Jason Kipnis small in stature, enormous in potential |publisher=Yahoo! Sports |date=July 20, 2011 |accessdate=July 24, 2011}}</ref><ref name="mlbdailydish1">{{cite news|last=Bopp |first=Justin |url=http://www.mlbdailydish.com/2011/7/21/2287487/cleveland-indians-call-up-jason-kipnis |title=Cleveland Indians Call Up Jason Kipnis |work=MLB Daily Dish |date= July 21, 2011|accessdate=July 24, 2011}}</ref> but by midseason ranked him 31st-best in the minors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aol.sportingnews.com/mlb/story/2011-07-21/indians-promote-2b-prospect-jason-kipnis |title=Indians promote 2B prospect Jason Kipnis |work=Sporting News |date= July 22, 2011|accessdate=July 24, 2011}}</ref>

In 2011, Kipnis was named the Indians Minor League Player of the Week for June 26&nbsp;<U+2013> July 2, after batting .500 with two home runs and a .581 on-base percentage. At that point in the season, Kipnis was 11-for-11 in stolen base attempts<ref name="2B Jason"/> and was leading the International League in runs scored (60) and triples (9). At that time he was also second in OPS (.914), fourth in slugging percentage (.525), fifth in on-base percentage (.389), tied for sixth in RBIs (50), tied for seventh in hits (90), twelfth in average (.305), tied for fifteenth in stolen bases (11), and tied for nineteenth in HRs (11).<ref name="2B Jason"/> On July 4, Kipnis was named the International League Player of the Week.<ref name="2B Jason"/>

Kipnis represented the Cleveland Indians in the 2011 [[All-Star Futures Game]] on July 10, hitting a 95-mph fastball for a home run when he led off the bottom of the first inning for the United States.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://cleveland.indians.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20110623&content_id=20912108&vkey=news_cle&c_id=cle |title=Drew Pomeranz, Jason Kipnis to represent Indians at Futures Game |publisher=mlb.com |date=June 23, 2011 |first=Zack |last=Meizel |accessdate=July 22, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Haller |first=Doug |url=http://www.azcentral.com/sports/diamondbacks/articles/2011/07/10/20110710mlb-all-star-futures-usa-win-world-jason-kipnis.html |title=Former ASU star Jason Kipnis leads Team USA over Team World in All-Star Futures Game |publisher=Azcentral.com |date=July 10, 2011 |author= |accessdate=July 22, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Badler |first=Ben |url=http://www.baseballamerica.com/today/prospects/futures-game/2011/2612053.html |title=Prospects: Futures Game Superlatives |work=Baseball America |date=July 10, 2011 |accessdate=July 24, 2011}}</ref> Kipnis also was named to the International League All-Star team, and he doubled and walked in the game on July 13.<ref name="2B Jason"/><ref>{{cite news|last=Phillips |first=Carron J. |url=http://www.sltrib.com/sltrib/sports/52187088-77/inning-inf-hit-game.html.csp |title=Triple-A All-Star Game: How the players did |work=The Salt Lake Tribune |date=July 14, 2011 |accessdate=July 24, 2011}}</ref>

On July 22, 2011, Kipnis was called up from the Clippers to the Cleveland Indians.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hardballtalk.nbcsports.com/2011/07/21/indians-call-up-top-prospect-jason-kipnis/ |title=Indians call up top prospect Jason Kipnis |publisher=NBC Sports |date= July 21, 2011|first= Matthew |last=Pouliot|accessdate=July 22, 2011}}</ref> At the time, he was leading the International league in triples (9), was second in runs scored (64), seventh in total bases (164), tied for tenth in walks (44), twelfth in RBIs (55), and seventeenth in stolen bases (12 in 13 attempts).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20110721&content_id=22118246&vkey=affililiate&c_id=cle |title=Tribe calls up touted prospect Jason Kipnis; Up-and-coming second baseman could see time in the outfield |publisher=mlb.com |date=July 21, 2011 |first=Jordan |last=Bastien |accessdate=July 24, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jewishbaseballnews.com/news-alert-indians-call-up-2b-jason-kipnis/ |title=News alert: Indians call up 2B Jason Kipnis |work=Jewish Baseball News |date=July 21, 2011 |accessdate=July 24, 2011}}</ref>

==Major leagues==
===Cleveland Indians (2011<U+2013>present)===
[[File:Jason Kipnis leaving batters box.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Kipnis in a game against the [[Baltimore Orioles]]]]
Kipnis made his major league debut on July 22, 2011, starting at second base against the [[Chicago White Sox]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://espn.go.com/mlb/story/_/id/6794140/cleveland-indians-call-jason-kipnis |title=Cleveland Indians call up Jason Kipnis |work=Associated Press|date=July 22, 2011 |author= |accessdate=July 19, 2012}}</ref> His first career hit came in his next game two days later&nbsp;<U+2013> a game-winning [[walk-off]] single with the [[bases loaded]] and two outs in the ninth inning against the [[Los Angeles Angels of Anaheim]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://chronicle.northcoastnow.com/2011/07/26/indians-3-angels-2-rally-ends-tribe-skid/ |title=Indians 3, Angels 2: Rally ends Tribe Skid |work=The Chronicle Telegram |date=July 26, 2011 |accessdate=July 19, 2012}}</ref> On August 3, 2011, Kipnis became the first Indians second baseman to hit a home run in four consecutive games, and the only Indian other than former Indians MVP [[Al Rosen]] to do so in his rookie year.<ref>{{cite news|author=Elise Amendola |url=http://www.cleveland.com/tribe/index.ssf/2011/08/jason_kipnis_on_a_hr_roll_clev.html |title=Jason Kipnis on a HR roll |author= |publisher=cleveland.com |date=August 5, 2006 |accessdate=August 5, 2011}}</ref> It was the first time in major league history that a player had homered in four consecutive games within two weeks of his major league debut.<ref>{{cite news|author= |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20110804&content_id=22740352&vkey=news_mlb&c_id=mlb |title=Show-stopper: Kipnis off to amazing start |publisher=mlb.com |date=July 31, 2011 |accessdate=August 5, 2011}}</ref> On August 10, Kipnis had a five-hit, four-run game, the first time a rookie had done so since [[Jim Fridley]] in 1952.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://cleveland.indians.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20110810&content_id=23057850&vkey=news_cle&c_id=cle |title=Kipnis Penning Quite the Rookie Campaign |work=MLB.com |date=August 10, 2011 |accessdate=August 11, 2011}}</ref> In 2011, he played 36 games in the major leagues and batted .272 with seven home runs and 19 RBIs.<ref name="Baseball Cube Statistics" />

Jason Kipnis got the Opening Day starting job at second base for 2012.<ref name="2012 starters">{{cite web|title=2012 Opening Day roster|url=http://www.letsgotribe.com/2012/4/1/2918194/cleveland-indians-2012-opening-day-roster|accessdate=October 23, 2012|author=APV|date=April 1, 2012}}</ref> On May 3, 2012, in a game against the Chicago White Sox, Kipnis had a triple, home run, and a career-high four RBIs in a 7-5 Indians victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.yahoo.com/news/kipnis-powers-indians-past-white-031725733--mlb.html|title=Kipnis powers Indians past White Sox 7-5|publisher=Associated Press|date=May 3, 2012|accessdate=May 4, 2012}}</ref> On June 1, Kipnis hit his first major league [[grand slam (baseball)|grand slam]] off [[Minnesota Twins]]' starting pitcher [[Carl Pavano]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=320601105|title=Jason Kipnis hits grand slam in Indians' rout of Twins|publisher=[[Associated Press]]|date=June 1, 2012|accessdate=July 29, 2012}}</ref> Kipnis played 152 games in 2012, batting .257 with 14 home runs and 76 RBIs.<ref name="Baseball Cube Statistics" />

==Personal life==
Kipnis is a practicing Roman Catholic, though he self-identifies as Jewish due to his father's Jewish ancestry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clevelandjewishnews.com/articles/2011/08/05/arts/jewish_stars/doc4e3ac9319e2c8895970568.txt |title=Jewish Stars|first=Nate |last=Bloom |publisher=Cleveland Jewish News |date=August 5, 2011 |accessdate=August 5, 2011}}</ref> Kipnis has been nicknamed "Dirtbag," since he is prone to get his uniform dirty during the course of a game.<ref name=Dirtbag /> Former Indians manager [[Manny Acta]] affectionately used the term when speaking about Kipnis in public.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cleveland.com/tribe/index.ssf/2012/05/jason_kipnis_growing_more_comf.html|title=Jason Kipnis growing more comfortable at second base: Cleveland Indians Insider|last=Manoloff|first=Dennis|work=The Plain Dealer|date=May 7, 2012|accessdate=May 8, 2012}}</ref>

